5|$|Children {{survived the}} Jastrebarsko and Donja Reka camps only because {{concerned}} individuals from Zagreb, Jastrebarsko, and surrounding villages offered humanitarian aid. Among {{those who worked}} to alleviate children's suffering were Marinić, Budisavljević, and Davila. One survivor, Milan Vujić, {{was taken from the}} camp when he was sick and cared for {{until the end of the}} war by a Croatian family in Koprivnica. They had never accepted the Ustaše regime or its policies. Many Croats, he stated, took in and even <b>adopted</b> <b>children</b> from Jastrebarsko and treated them kindly.|$|E
